We need to judge if visualization is misleading based on description. The description: line graph of expected vs observed deaths weekly from April 2019 to Oct 2020. Expected line stable, observed spikes in April 2020, then declines. Caption mentions Covid-19 and indirect deaths. The analysis says this supports claim that Covid caused excess mortality.

Potential issues: Is there cherry-picking? They show only up to Oct 2020, maybe later data could show different trends. But showing a period that includes the pandemic is appropriate. Could be causal inference: they claim pandemic caused excess mortality, which may be true but they attribute all excess to pandemic indirectly. That's a causal claim, but the data alone (observed vs expected) doesn't prove causality; other factors could contribute. However, likely the pandemic is main cause. Still, inferring causality from correlation may be a mild causal inference error.

Any axis issues? Y-axis from 55k to 75k, not starting at zero. That's typical for line graphs showing deaths; truncated axis can exaggerate differences. The divergence looks large; starting at 55k makes the spike appear bigger relative. That could be considered truncated axis (not zero). Might be misleading if they want to emphasize the spike. However the range is appropriate to show variation; but a zero baseline would be far off. Usually deaths per week cannot be zero; but truncated axis is a common subtle exaggeration. So possible "Truncated axis".

Any unclear encoding? Seems clear.

Dual axis? No.

Cherry-picking? They only show up to Oct 2020; maybe later months decline further; but the focus is pandemic period.

Causal inference: yes, they claim pandemic caused excess mortality, but that is plausible.

So we identify at least two error types: Truncated axis, Causal inference, possibly Cherry-picking (if selection of timeframe). Also possibly Failure to account for statistical nuance (no confidence intervals, expected deaths perhaps modeled with uncertainty). But not explicitly.
